<title>December 12, 1995 Press Release</title>
<body>
<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
December 12, 1995<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- 202-393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>
<p>
<center><h4><i>* MEDIA ADVISORY *</i></h4>
<p>
<h4>You are cordially invited to a Family Research Council symposium
on a</h4>
<p>
<h2>&quot;WORLD WITHOUT WELFARE&quot;</h2></center>
<p>
<B>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> Family Research Council will host a
symposium entitled, &quot;A World Without Welfare,&quot; on <B>Wednesday,
Dec. 13</B> <B>at The Willard Hotel in Washington, D.C. from 9
a.m. - 5 p.m. </B>in which various grass roots leaders and policy
makers will discuss the current and future state of welfare reform.
The symposium will seek to highlight the role government programs
play in promoting cultural decay, provide a philosophical framework
for social conservatives' involvement in dismantling the welfare
state, and create a sense of urgency about the need to cultivate
charitable alternatives at the grassroots. 
<p>
Confirmed symposium schedule:
<p><dl>
<dt><b>9:00 - 9:40:</b>
<dd>Dr. Michael Novak, American Enterprise Institute
<p>
<dt><b>9:50-10:50:</b>
<dd>David Frum, Author of <i>Dead Right</i>;<br>
Father Robert Sirico, Acton Institute
<p>
<dt><b>11:00-12:00:</b>
<dd>William Mattox, Vice President of Policy at Family Research Council;<br>
Michael Gerson, Policy Director for Senator Dan Coats;<br>
Peter Ferrara, Chief Economist at Americans for Tax Reform;<br>
John P. Walters, President of the New Citizenship Project;<br>
Robert Rector, Senior Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation
<p>
<dt><b>12:15-1:25 (Lunch):</b>
<dd>Marvin Olasky, Author of <i>The Tragedy of American Compassion</i>
<p>
<dt><b>1:40-2:00:</b>
<dd>Father Robert Sirico presents Acton Institute's 1995 Good Samaritan 
Awards to three model charitable programs.
<p>
<dt><b>2:00-2:30:</b>
<dd>Dr. John Perkins, Author of <i>Beyond Charity</i>, Publisher 
of <i>Urban Family</i>
<p>
<dt><b>2:45-3:15:</b>
<dd>Dr. Virgil Gulker, Director of Kids/Hope/USA in Michigan
<p>
<dt><b>3:15-5:00:</b>
<dd>Don Eberly, Director of the Civil Society Project;<br>
Robert Woodson, President of the National Center for Neighborhood
Enterprise;<br>
Rev. Ronald Moore, Mississippi Faith and Families Program;<br>
Terrence Scanlon, President of Capital Research Center;<br>
Adam Meyerson, <I>Policy Review</I>;<br>
Heather Higgins, Executive Director of the Council on Culture
and Community
<p></dl>
