<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 9, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



 


	


	For almost two decades Ralph Nader and his followers badgered car manufacturers to install airbags in every automobile. Eventually the Naderites got their way, and since 1991 all new passenger vehicles have been required by federal law to include these devices at an increased cost to car buyers of about $500 per vehicle. Now it is being publicly admitted that airbags are unsafe for children and small adults. Trouble seems to be that the airbags, which explode out of their housing at 200mph, will give you a powerful whack. For long-armed adults sitting well back in the seat, airbags do a fine job of cushioning the abdomen from the force of a head-on collision. But the same device will hit a child or a small adult in the face, producing head and neck injuries, sometimes fatal.
<P>
	In time, the manufacturers will probably succeed in fine-tuning airbags, but the existing 12 million cars equipped with the first generation will remain as testimony to the dangers of federal mandates. Every safety innovation involves costs and risks, whose consequences are different from different people—individuals should be permitted to do their own evaluating.


</blockquote>


