<title>Daily Commentary - December 9, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 9, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Honor. It's the missing word in modern English.  Honor is
a respect for norms, for history and tradition.  Honor is courage
fused with a deep humility.  Above all, honor is profound honesty.

<p>

But honor today is in trouble.  Just how much trouble is
obvious in a news report about the Congressional Medal of Honor.
It seems that the company that manufactures this prized award
has been doing a little business on the side.  It has been selling
duplicate copies of the medal to whoever is willing to pay.  You
heard me right.  For seventy-five dollars, you're a Congressional
Medal of Honor winner. The Congressional Medal of Honor is rarely
given.  Only the most unusual acts of bravery and self-sacrifice
-- extraordinary valor they call it -- qualify.  The Medal is
sometimes given to a grieving widow, parents pierced to the heart,
a now fatherless child.  None of these things has a commercial
price.

<p>

Once in a while an event comes along that captures vividly
how far we've fallen.  The case of the bogus medals is one of
those events.  America needs to recover its sense of honor.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

