<title>Daily Commentary - December 11, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 11, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

You probably haven't heard of the basketball team from Mount
Zion Christian Academy in Durham, North Carolina, but chances
are you'll soon hear a lot about them.  Many sportswriters and
scouts are calling them possibly the best high school team ever
assembled.

<p>

That in itself is interesting, but this team of athletic
stars is &quot;best&quot; in another and deeper sense, too.  They
are a nucleus of young men brought together as much on the basis
of their dismal past as their bright future.  This Christian school,
led by Pastor Donald Fozard, committed itself long ago to using
basketball to reach boys' souls.  The kids Fozard has taken in
are a motley crew of ex drop-outs, &quot;fall-through-the cracks&quot;
young men.  At Mt. Zion, they experience school as a disciplined
environment.  There are runs at five in the morning, mandatory
church twice-a-week, team prayers.  They are not allowed to date,
swear, listen to rap music, or wear jewelry.

<p>

The focus at Mt. Zion is on character and on the long-term
future -- on right and wrong and on faith.  And that focus is
taking Mt. Zion straight to the top.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

