<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 31, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 31, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

During his presidency, Bill Clinton's Secret Service detail
has had a sometimes-stormy relationship with the public.  The
latest incident occurred at the National Cathedral on Christmas
Eve.

<p>

The Rev. Bob Schenck got close enough to Clinton to whisper,
&quot;God will hold you to account, Mr. President.&quot;  According
to Schenck, Clinton heard the remark and understood it as Schenck
meant it -- a reference to the Presidential veto of the partial-birth
abortion ban.  In any event, when the service was over, Secret
Service agents detained Schenck, rifling through his wallet. 
They denied him a lawyer, and told him Clinton had complained
about Schenck's words.

<p>

As I noted, this isn't the first time Secret Service agents
have made life unpleasant for people who dare speak to Clinton.
What Schenck reportedly said is hardly a threat.  In fact, every
one of us will be held accountable by God -- for what we've done,
or failed to do, to show mercy, or kindness, or love.  And on
that day of judgment, none of us will have Secret Service agents
at our side to shield us from the truth.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

