<P>
<B>The New Paradigm on Environmental Enforcement: Environmental
Audit Privilege and Immunity Legislation,</B>
<br>by R. Kinnan Golemon and Laura Wolf
<P>
<I>The State Factor</I>, Vol. 22, No. 1, American Legislative
Exchange Council<HR>

<P>
R. Kinnan Golemon, a prominent expert in the field of Environmental
Law, and Laura Wolf, an environmental lawyer in Austin, present
a new paradigm for environmental enforcement. For the last twenty-five
years environmental regulation has focused on the &quot;command
and control&quot; model. Golemon and Wolf argue that this model,
which has developed an extremely complicated regulatory scheme,
is outdated and needs to change. They believe that a new environmental
regulatory model should focus on and encourage voluntary compliance.
Goleman and Wolf present &quot;audit privileges and penalty immunities&quot;
as part of the solution. These give an incentive for regulated
entities to conduct environmental audits without the fear of major
sanctions. The audits will promote candid, effective discussions
within the regulated entities to help find the causes of, and
the solution to, environmental noncompliance. They will also remove
the incentive to not identify or hide noncompliance so that the
problem can be solved in the most constructive possible way. 13
pp.  CONTACT: American Legislative Exchange Council, 910 17th
Street, N.W., 5th floor, Washington, DC  20006, 202/466-3800,
fax 202/466-3801.
<P>
<B>Privatizing the Public Lands, <BR>
</B>by B. Delworth Gardner
<P>
<I>Focus on Utah</I>, No. 1, Sutherland Institute<HR>

<P>
B. Delworth Gardner, Professor Emeritus of Economics at Brigham
Young University, argues that the federal government should dispose
of its public land in the West, and permit private parties to
own and control the land itself. According to Gardner, private
management is superior to public management in conserving resources.
In economic markets, the future generations are represented by
entrepreneurs who will profit from, and are most interested in,
conserving resources for their future use. She continues by stressing
that consumers and taxpayers are the beneficiaries if market products,
in this case, land use user fees, are priced at competitive levels.
Although some public management products appear to be free or
subsidized, taxpayers must pay for such things as the lobbying,
campaign contributions, propaganda, and court costs that are incurred
in order to influence public decisions. Privatization and market
allocation at a price would make it so each consumer would pay
for what he gets. Resources would be more productive, and products
would increase in variety in order to be tailored toward consumer
tastes. If private entrepreneurs marketed hunting and fishing
privileges, they would manage the resources more efficiently and
more successfully. Private firms also have a greater incentive
to stop undesirable managerial behavior than government bureaucrats.
Finally, Gardner argues that the federal government should gradually
dispose of the public lands, and they should try alternative ways
for privatizing the public lands, such as long-term competitive
leasing of public lands to private groups. 17 pp. CONTACT: Sutherland
Institute, 111 East 5600 South, Suite 208, Murray, UT 84107, 801/281-2081,
fax 801/281-2412, e-mail <a href="mailto:sutherland@utah-inter.net">sutherland@utah-inter.net.</a>
<P>
<B>Energy R&amp;D Spending: Not Even &quot;Success Stories&quot;
Measure Up,</B><br>
by John Tottie
<P>
<I>Issue Analysis</I>, No. 36, Citizens for a Sound Economy<HR>

<P>
John Tottie, Senior Economist for Tax and Budget at Citizens for
a Sound Economy, examines the $47 billion in research and development
(R&amp;D) spending by the Department of Energy (DOE)-supposedly
for the benefit of taxpayers and the U.S. economy. In the early
days of the 104th Congress, DOE published &quot;Success Stories:
The Energy Mission in the Marketplace,&quot; highlighting what
the department thought were its successes in applied energy research
and development. The 22 page report seems like an attempt to fight
off the much needed reductions in the bloated spending by DOE
on R&amp;D. Tottie argues that the private industry that stands
to benefit from the R&amp;D spending, not taxpayers, should be
responsible for the costs associated with developing scientific
knowledge that has specific commercial applications.  8 pp. CONTACT:
Citizens for a Sound Economy, 1250 H Street, N.W., Suite 700,
Washington, DC 20005-3908, 202/783-3870, fax 202/783-4687, Internet
<a href="http://www.cse.org/cse">http://www.cse.org/cse.</a>
<P>
<B>A National Survey of Attitudes on <BR>
Environmental Policy</B>
<P>
Competitive Enterprise Institute<HR>

<P>
The Competitive Enterprise Institute commissioned <I>The Polling
Company</I> to perform a nationwide poll of 1,000 registered voters
nationwide. They found that most Americans support environmental
protection, but are not activists. They also found that most Americans
support a greater role for state and local governments in environmental
policy, and that state and local governments are better suited
at addressing environmental concerns than the federal government.
According to the survey, most Americans see devolution, regulatory
reform, and property rights as being consistent with environmental
protection. Also, Americans see nothing anti-environment about
alternative approaches to environmental policy. CEI argues that
the challenge for supporters of environmental regulatory reform
is to articulate a vision for the future of environmental policy
that combines the public's concern for environmental protection
with their preference for limited government policies. Americans
have come to realize that extensive federal bureaucracies are
not necessary to advance environmental protection, and that pursuing
environmental reform is not &quot;anti-environment.&quot; 25 pp.
CONTACT: Competitive Enterprise Institute, 1001 Connecticut Avenue,
N.W., Suite 1250, Washington, DC 20036, 202/331-1010, fax 202/488-0806.
<P>
<B>A New Environmental Tool? Assessing Life Cycle Assessment,
</B> 
<br>
by Mark Duda and Jane Shaw
<P>
<I>Contemporary Issues Series</I>, No. 81, Center for the Study
of American Business<HR>

<P>
&quot;Life cycle assessment&quot; (LCA) is a process that attempts
to measure the total environmental impact of a product and its
manufacturing process. Mark Duda, Fellow at the Political Economy
Research Center (PERC), and Jane Shaw, a Senior Associate of PERC,
discuss the reasons why this procedure should not be used to shape
public policy. According to Duda and Shaw, LCA is useful to companies
that want to know whether the raw material they use might become
scarce or become environmentally harmful. When companies use LCA
their data is generally reliable and their goals are usually clear.
If such procedures were used for public policy and regulatory
purposes, argue Duda and Shaw, it would require that practitioners
use data from a wide range of sources and then translate this
data into environmental impacts. The averages and aggregates produced
would be inaccurate and would not describe the differences between
one product and another. According to Duda and Shaw, it is hard
to translate resource consumption and emissions data into actual
environmental impacts. For example it does not take into consideration
the environment in which production occurs. Overall, they conclude,
LCA makes sense for individual firms, which use it to plan how
they will respond to environmental regulations and to the environmental
concerns of their customers. If LCA information is collected at
the industry level it is not sufficiently accurate for making
broad public policy decisions.  20 pp. CONTACT: Center for the
Study of American Business, Washington University, Campus Box
1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630, fax 314/935-5688.
<P>
<B>A Turf Fight for Indoor Air Quality Protection, <BR>
</B>by Dwight Lee
<P>
<I>Contemporary Issues Series</I>, No. 79, Center for the Study
of American Business<HR>

<P>
Dwight Lee, an Adjunct Fellow for the Center for the Study of
American Business, discusses the bureaucratic turf war over the
control and regulation of indoor air. The Occupational Safety
and Health Administration (OSHA) has jurisdiction over workplace
safety and is in a fight with the Environmental Protection Agency
over jurisdiction of indoor air quality (IAQ) in the workplace.
The agency that is able to gain control over IAQ will be in a
good position to expand its budget and power. According to Lee,
EPA and OSHA are using the political issue of tobacco smoke to
muscle for their larger budgets. OSHA has made a proposal to ban
smoking in all work sites under its jurisdiction. According to
Lee, OSHA's position relies on flawed and biased studies that
emphasize that indoor pollution can be addressed by singling out
particular pollutants such as tobacco smoke. In reality, indoor
air pollution is a general problem that cannot be effectively
dealt with by singling out particular pollutants. Lee argues that
OSHA ignores cost saving alternative approaches, ignores the advantages
of market incentives and exaggerates the benefits of regulation.
Overall, it exploits the politically contentious issue of tobacco
to grab for more power. Lee concludes that the only argument that
can be made for OSHA IAQ regulation is that it would be no more
inefficient than EPA regulation.  16 pp. CONTACT: Center for the
Study of American Business, Washington University, Campus Box
1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630, fax 314/935-5688.
<P>
<B>Clean Air and Emerging Alternative Fuel Vehicles: A Time for
Environmental Innovation Areas,</B><br>
by Bruce Yandle, Andy Barnett, and Mark Brandly
<P>
<I>Future Insight</I>, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation<HR>

<P>
Bruce Yandle, an Adjunct Fellow at The Progress &amp; Freedom
Foundation, Andy Barnett, Associate Professor of Economics at
Auburn University, and Mark Brandly, a doctoral candidate in economics
at Auburn, call for the creation of Environmental Innovation Areas
(EIAs). EIAs will recognize that different regions face different
environmental and pollution problems. Different regions should
be given flexibility to meet clean air requirements in ways that
are best suited for their particular area, instead of the top-down
command and control system that we currently have. Yandle, Barnett
and Brandly call for an end to federal fuel taxes that discriminate
against alternative fuels. With EIAs, states and regions could
design fuel taxes that encourage the appropriate use of cleaner
burning fuels for their area. Changing the laws that discriminate
against alternative fuel vehicles will be a lower cost way to
improve automobile efficiency and a reduction in American reliance
on imported petroleum than Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE)
standards. 57 pp. CONTACT: Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation,
1301 K Street, N.W., Suite 650 West, Washington, D.C., 20005,
202/289-8928, fax 202/289-6079, e-mail: <a href="mailto:mail@pff.org">mail@pff.org</a>, Internet: <a href="http://www.pff.org">http://www.pff.org</a>
<P>
<B>The Privatization Process: A Worldwide Perspective,</B>
<br>
Edited by Terry Anderson and Peter Hill<HR>

<P>
The editors of this collection of essays, Terry Anderson, Executive
Director of PERC (the Political Economy Research Center), and
Peter Hill, a Senior Associate of PERC, argue that the 1980s and
1990s will be remembered in history as the era of privatization.
The trend of privatization, which was in part, inspired by the
collapse of the former Soviet Union, is being hotly debated throughout
American government. This book is a collection of original essays
by distinguished scholars that examine the potential benefits,
as well as the possible pitfalls, of national and global privatization.
This book also provides several perspective on how privatization
can best be achieved. With the support of empirical evidence,
the various authors asses the institutional changes and economic
impact of this worldwide trend. 270 pp. CONTACT: Rowman &amp;
Littlefield Publishers, 4720 Boston Way, Lanham, MD 20706, 800/462-6420.
<P><HR>
<a name="crime"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>CRIME &AMP; LAW</FONT></CENTER>

<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1089b.html">Getting Backup: Twenty-One Steps Public Officials Can Take to Support Their Local Police, </a></B><br>
by Bob Moffit and Ed Meese
<P>
<I>Backgrounder</I> No. 1089, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Bob Moffit, Deputy Director of Domestic Policy Studies at The
Heritage Foundation, and Ed Meese, former Attorney General of
The United States and Ronald Reagan Distinguished Fellow at The
Heritage Foundation, present twenty-one steps that public officials
can take to support their local police. Moffit and Meese draw
upon the success of former New York City Commissioner of Police
William Bratton's short tenure, in which serious crime dropped
36 percent, including a 44 percent drop in auto theft and a 45
percent drop in murder. A reduction in crime does not depend upon
new cars or computers, more officers and bigger budgets. What
is most important, this paper says, is solid personnel management
and a clear mission for combating crime and disorder, with support
from the public, the state and the courts, and the press. Moffit
and Meese give the following suggestions for specific ways that
local officials can strengthen their police forces through their
own efforts: police should have a more back to basics role; police
should combat minor &quot;disorder&quot; crimes that provide an
environment for more serious crimes; raise the standards for who
can become a police officer; improve police compensation; target
hot spots; and reduce caseloads for detectives, among other suggestions.
Moffit and Meese call on the federal government to: block the
appointment of federal judges who demonstrate an insensitivity
to public safety; review federal statutes dealing with crime,
and repeal the ones that impinge on the legitimate authority of
local and state law enforcement officials; review the impact of
the <I>Miranda</I> ruling; and pursue ways through enterprise
zones to revitalize inner-city neighborhoods among other suggestions.
Overall, states and localities need maximum flexibility to combat
violent crime. 37 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999,
202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a> Internet  <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/govern/gip10.html">Organized Crime, Organized Labor, and Corruption of the Federal
Grants Process, </a><BR>
</B>by Ken Weinstein
<P>
<I>Government Integrity Project Report</I>, No. 10, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Ken Weinstein, Director of the Government Reform Project at the
Heritage Foundation, reports that under the Clinton Administration
a string of federal grants have continued to subsidize the Laborers'
International Union of North America (LIUNA) even as government
investigators were uncovering evidence of organized criminal influence
in the union. Weinstein argues that restrictions or elimination
of grants to politically active groups such as unions should be
seriously considered by Congress. Meanwhile, Congress should act
immediately to: require that relevant grantmakers at certain federal
bureaus testify about their knowledge of allegations of criminal
infiltration of LIUNA; prohibit organizations whose officers have
records of criminal wrongdoing from receiving federal grants;
renew efforts to restrict lobbying by federal grantees; and order
a General Accounting Office investigation into LIUNA's handling
of federal grants. Weinstein concludes by pointing out that it
is bad enough that mandatory dues from union members are used
to pay for corruption and political activities, tax payers should
not have to pay as well. 9 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The
Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington,
D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>,  Internet  <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B>Civil Right and Sexual Behavior: An Analysis of the Employment
Non-Discrimination Act, <BR>
</B>by Paul Mero
<P>
<I>Insight</I>, Family Research Council<HR>

<P>
Paul Mero, a political consultant and congressional staffer, examines
how the Employment Non-Discrimination Act might lead to the adoption
of the entire homosexual rights agenda. He argues that organized
homosexuality, the political pragmatic side of the homosexuality
movement, has narrowly worded this bill as a calculated risk that
the final determination of this legislation will rest on some
very fundamental notions about homosexuality <I>per se</I>, and
whether or not mainstream America will accept these notions. According
to Mero, the narrowly worded language of the legislation is very
ambiguous and includes the curious term &quot;bisexual.&quot;
Mero says this term is one of the calculated risks with which
organized homosexuality is testing mainstream America. &quot;Bisexual,&quot;
is a person that has sex with both men and women. Unlike the word
&quot;lesbianism&quot; or &quot;homosexuality,&quot; which some
of the public can accept as possibly genetic traits, bisexuality
cannot be taken seriously, according to Mero. He argues that amending
the 1964 Civil Rights Act with the word &quot;bisexual&quot; would
be the same as society granting its crowning approval of promiscuous
sexual activity and to renounce marriage and traditional mores.
It would be no different than implying that promiscuity is a genetic
trait. Or it seriously confuses behavior with orientation. Mero
concludes by showing how organized homosexuality has exploited
the Hate Crimes Bill to further their agenda. They did it claiming
victimhood, confusing homosexuality with innate human properties
such as skin color, using bogus studies to support quantitative
claims of discrimination, winning the endorsement of former &quot;conservative&quot;
Republicans, and taking the media along for the ride with their
disregard for facts. Many of the same components exist for the
Employment Non-Discrimination Act. 17 pp. CONTACT: Family Research
Council, 700 13th Street, N.W., Suite 500, Washington, DC  20005,
202/393-2100, fax 202/393-2134, Internet <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC/">http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC/</a>
<P>
<B>Feminist Jurisprudence: Equal Rights or Neo-Paternalism?</B>
<br>by Michael Weiss and Cathy Young
<P>
<I>Policy Analysis</I> No. 256, Cato Institute<HR>

<P>
Cato Associate Policy Analyst, Cathy Young, and University of
Houston Law Professor, Michael Weiss, argue that the rise of feminist
jurisprudence has gone far beyond the original and widely supported
goal of equal treatment for both sexes. According to Young and
Weiss, the new feminist legal theory agenda is to redistribute
power from the &quot;dominant class&quot; (men) to the &quot;subordinate
class&quot; (women), while such key concepts of Western jurisprudence
as judicial neutrality and individual rights are declared to be
patriarchal fictions designed to protect male privilege. Some
feminist-initiated legal reforms have addressed real wrongs such
as the inadequate protection for victims of domestic violence.
However, say Young and Weiss, feminist legal theory has resulted
in increasingly loose and subjective definitions of harassment
and rape, dangerous moves to eviscerate the presumption of innocence
in sexual assault cases, and a broad concept of self-defense in
cases of battered wives. The authors conclude that Courts and
legislatures should not limit individual rights and reaffirm the
fundamental principle of the classical liberal origins of the
movement for women's rights: equality before the law regardless
of gender. 63 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490,
E-mail <a href="cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org, </a>Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org/">http://www.cato.org/</a>
<P>
<B>Washington Legal Foundation</B>
<P>
Recent Publications<HR>

<P><ul>
<li> <B>Will Guidelines Clarify Role of Antitrust Law in Health Care?</B>
by Bruce Stewart and E. John Stern, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>.
This paper examines how the antitrust laws prevent doctors from
entering into strategic alliances and provides advice to antitrust
regulators, who are currently drafting new guidelines for the
health care field, on how best to balance the goals of preventing
anti-competitive activities and encouraging cost containment.
4 pp.
<P>
<li> <B>Court Questions Constitutionality of Federal Environmental
Laws, </B>by Richard Kuntz, <I>Legal Backgrounder</I>. Kuntz examines
the finding by a Alabama federal district court, that the Superfund
law was unconstitutional, as applied to a specific clean-up action.
The paper focuses on the court's determination that the Superfund
law violates the Constitution's Interstate Commerce Clause and
that it imposes liability retroactively, violating due process.
4 pp. 
<P>
<li> <B>State Property Right Protection Statutes: A Reassessment,
</B>by Timothy Bishop and Jeffrey Sarles, <I>Working Paper</I>.
Bishop and Sarles examine the state-level efforts to ensure compensation
for land owners when government action &quot;takes&quot; their
property. The authors examine the unsuccessful campaign in Washington
state to enact broad protection for property rights and conclude
that we still need to focus on setting favorable precedents in
federal and state courts. 14 pp. CONTACT: Washington Legal Foundation,
2009 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20036, 202/588-0302,
fax 202/588-0386.
</ul>
<P>
<B>Symposium on Law and the Family</B>
<P>
<I>Notre Dame Journal of Law, Ethics &amp; Public Policy</I><HR>

<P>
This issue of <I>Notre Dame Journal of Law, Ethics &amp; Public
Policy</I> is a symposium on law and the family. Included articles
are: &quot;Marriage, Family and the Positive Law,&quot; by Teresa
Stanton Collett, Visiting Professor of Law at Notre Dame Law School;
&quot;Parent and Child in Conflict: Between Liberty and Responsibility,&quot;
by Melinda Roberts, Assistant Professor of Philosophy, Trenton
State College; &quot;The Indian Child Welfare Act of 1978: Violating
Personal Rights for the Sake of the Tribe,&quot; by Christine
Bakeis, Associate, Kasdorf, Lewis &amp; Swietlik; &quot;Homosexual
Marriage and the Myth of Tolerance: Is Cardinal O'Connor a 'Homophobe'?,&quot;
by Richard Duncan, Professor of Law, University of Nebraska; and,
&quot;Sex Education and Condom Distribution: John, Susan, Parents,
and Schools,&quot; by Jeffrey Caruso, J.D., 1996, Notre Dame Law
School. 200 pp. CONTACT: <I>Notre Dame Journal of Law, Ethics
&amp; Public Policy</I>, Thomas White Center on Law &amp; Government,
Notre Dame Law School, Notre Dame, Indiana 46556, 219/631-5913.
<P><HR>
<a name="elections"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>ELECTIONS
&AMP; GOVERNING</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/congress">Reviewing the Revolution: Conservative Successes in the 104th Congress</a></B>
<P>
The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
The Heritage Foundation has examined what successes the 104th
Congress has had in achieving conservative goals. Despite setbacks,
bad public relations and Presidential vetoes, the 104th Congress
has been successful in meeting conservative's high expectations
in several key areas. Overall they began a revolutionary reversal
of failed liberal policies in such areas as welfare, agriculture,
and regulation. Significant steps have been taken to reduce the
size of the federal government and to empower states, local communites,
and individuals. 72 pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999,
202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B>I &amp; R Across America</B>
<P>
Americans for Tax Reform<HR>

<P>
This publication by Americans for Tax Reform is a chart of information
about the initiative and referendum campaigns currently underway
in the states. It lists the state, the subject of legislation,
how many valid signatures are required to qualify for the ballot,
the deadline for getting the initiative on the ballot and whether
the initiative is to amend the state constitution, to make a new
law, or a referred measure by the state legislature. Also included
is a list of respective state offices that can be reached for
initiative and referendum status. 16 pp. CONTACT: Americans for
Tax Reform, 1320 18th Street, N.W., Suite 200, Washington, DC
20036, 202/785-0266, fax 202/785-0261, Internet  <BR>
<a href="http://www.atr.org/">http://www.atr.org/</a>
<P>
<B>Statewide Initiatives on the 1996 General Election Ballot,
</B><br>
by Kenneth Mulligan
<P>
Free Congress Foundation<HR>

<P>
This report lists the statewide ballot initiatives that will appear
on the 1996 general election ballot. There are four parts to the
report. Part one lists the states that have the initiative and
popular referendum. Part two is a table of the statewide ballot
initiatives, sorted by states. Part three, the body of the report,
lists the statewide ballot initiatives, sorted by state. Part
four is a table of the statewide ballot initiatives, sorted by
category. 18 pp.  CONTACT: Free Congress Foundation, 717 Second
Street, N.E., Washington, DC  20002, 202/546-3000, fax 202/543-8425,
Internet <a href="http://net.fcref.org">http://net.fcref.org</a>
<P>
<B>1996 International Directory of Election Offices,</B><br>
edited and compiled by Susanna DeBusk
<P>
International Foundation for Election Systems<HR>

<P>
The International Foundation for Election Systems (IFES) has produced
the <I>International Directory of Election Offices</I>. This directory
provides the election authorities contact information and a description
of the bodies responsible for election administration for 144
countries. The descriptions have been written by the bodies themselves
so as to provide a comparison of how governments have chosen to
meet demands for a just electoral system. 154 pp. CONTACT: International
Foundation for Election Systems, 1101 15th Street, N.W., Third
Floor, Washington, D.C. 2005, 202/828-8507.
<P><HR>
<a name="culture"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>CULTURE &AMP; COMMUNITY</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/ib228.html">Saving Our Children: The American Community Renewal Act of 1996</a>,</B><br>
by Christine Olson and Robert Rector
<P>
<I>Issue Bulletin</I>, No. 228, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
According to Christine Olson, Policy Analyst at The Heritage Foundation,
and Robert Rector, Senior Policy Analyst at The Heritage Foundation,
The American Community Renewal Act of 1996 (H.R. 3467) will promote
the moral renewal and economic revitalization of America's most
poverty-stricken urban and rural areas. The bill is sponsored
by Representatives J.C. Watts (OK) and James Talent (MO). It will
use tax incentives, regulatory relief, innovative school reform
pilot projects and homeownership incentives for areas of high
rates of poverty, crime, welfare dependency, joblessness, and
poor schools. Olson and Rector argue that the bill will achieve:
increased job creation; small business expansion and formation;
moral renewal; expanded educational opportunities; greater private
philanthropy to aid the poor; and greater participation by religious
organizations in providing services to the poor. This bill gives
Congress and the Administration an opportunity to change the way
the federal government has been involved in community development
over the last 30 years. The bill realizes that what our nation's
poorest communities need more than larger benefits checks from
the government is economic conditions that enable depressed communities
to become more profitable places for work and businesses. Olson
and Rector conclude that this bill represents an excellent opportunity
to make a bipartisan stand for children by tackling the root causes
of poverty, crime, and illegitimacy. 18 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain,
The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington,
D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/ib227.html">How Congress Can Protect The Rights of Parents to Raise Their Children</a>,</B>
<br>by Pat Fagan and Wade Horn
<P>
<I>Issue Bulletin</I>, No. 227, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
Pat Fagan, William H. G. FitzGerald Fellow in Family and Cultural
Studies at The Heritage Foundation, and Wade Horn, Director of
The National Fatherhood Initiative, illustrate how Congress can
protect the rights of parents to raise their children. They argue
that the Parental Rights and Responsibilities Act, introduced
by Senator Charles Grassley (IA) and Representative Steve Largent
(OK), will give parents superior standing over government and
its agencies in their children's education and in the protection
and formation of their children's moral character. Fagan and Horn
point out that the bill will declare that parents' rights to direct
the upbringing of their children are fundamental rights which
government can curtail only under conditions of &quot;compelling
interest&quot; and under &quot;strict guidelines&quot; of judicial
procedure, legal terms which guide courts in their decisions.
Overall, they say, the rights of parents as a group are disregarded
or endangered in too many cases by government officials. According
to Fagan and Horn, because of the persistent danger to the fundamental
rights of parents from state court rulings, professional associations,
government bureaucracies, the educational establishment, and international
agencies and bodies, parental rights need codification into law.
27 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214
Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/608-6058,
fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org, </a>Internet  http://www.heritage.org.
<P>
<B><a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bgup279.html">The Clinton Administration's Continuing Retreat in the War
on Drugs,</a></B>
<br>
by John Walters and James O'Gara
<P>
<I>Backgrounder Update</I>, No. 270, The Heritage Foundation<HR>

<P>
John Walters, President of the New Citizenship Project, and James
O'Gara, Director of Research for the New Citizenship Project,
call for President Clinton to exercise leadership in the war on
drugs. They report that he has a poor record in this area. Interdiction
efforts and prosecution for illegal drugs are down, illegal drug
usage and emergency room admissions are up. Walters and O'Gara
argue that part of the problem has been not appointing effective
leaders in key positions to articulate and enforce a strong antidrug
message, and inappropriate reductions in staff at agencies dedicated
to fighting drugs on the front lines. They call on Congress to
focus federal efforts on law enforcement and programs that work,
and fund only those rehabilitation programs that have a track
record of success. One way to do this is to allow funding for
drug counseling and rehabilitation programs provided by religious
organizations. Walters and O'Gara conclude that American taxpayers
deserve presidential leadership on this issue, and the complexity
of the issue is not an excuse for ineffective policy and lack
of serious effort. 15 pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999,
202/608-6058, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail <a href="mailto:Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>, Internet  <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<P>
<B>Culture Wars in America,</B><br>
by Edward Lazear
<P>
<I>Essays in Public Policy</I>, Hoover Institution<HR>

<P>
Edward Lazear, Hoover Senior Fellow, discusses how the culture
wars in America threaten our ability to absorb new immigrants,
and to benefit from the diversity already present in the United
States. He argues that much of the conflict of the culture wars
in America is generated by government policies that reduce the
incentives to become assimilated and emphasize the differences
in the population. Some examples that Lazear lists are: education
in one's native language; unbalanced immigration policies that
result in large and stable ghettos, welfare availability; and
encouragement of a multilingual society by allowing citizens to
vote in languages other than English. Lazear explores patterns
of cultural assimilation and makes recommendations on policy related
to immigration, education, and language that may lead to an end
of the culture wars. 32 pp. CONTACT: Hoover Institution Press,
Stanford University Press, Stanford, CA  94305-6010, 415/723-3373,
fax 415/723-1687, Internet <a href="http://hoover.stanford.edu">http://hoover.stanford.edu</a>.
<P>
<B>Federal Drug War Ignoring Great Ally: Faith-Based Treatment,
</B><br>
by Robert Maginnis
<P>
<I>Insight</I>, Family Research Council<HR>

<P>
Robert Maginnis, Senior Policy Analyst at the Family Research
Council, illustrates how the government is actively discouraging
some of the most effective programs from drug treatment. Faith-based
drug treatment programs have consistently produced the highest
&quot;cure&quot; rates in the country for treating drug abusers.
State and federal agencies have tried to shut down several faith
based drug treatment centers because their practitioners did not
have proper medical qualifications This is despite the fact that
faith-based treatment has had much higher success rates at a fraction
of the cost of government endorsed centers. Maginnis says that
there are two differing schools of thought on the root causes
of drug addiction. Government agencies mostly believe that it
is a disease and should be treated as such. Faith based treatment
sees addiction as beginning with a moral problem and that treatment
requires an acceptance of moral absolutes. Maginnis says that
as far as drug treatment goes, one size does not fit all. Therefore
a diversity of treatment alternatives, including low cost taxpayer-free
and faith based programs must be available. The government should
not try to fight the drug war alone when the local faith community
can play a vital role in prevention and treatment. 12 pp. CONTACT:
Family Research Council, 700 13th Street, N.W., Suite 500, Washington,
DC  20005, 202/393-2100, fax 202/393-2134, Internet <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC">http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC</a>
<P>
<B>The Economic Way of Looking at Behavior: The Nobel Lecture,</B><br>
by Gary Becker

<P>
<I>Essays in Public Policy</I>, Hoover Institution<HR>

<P>Gary Becker, Nobel laureate in economics and Hoover Senior Fellow,
was recognized by the Royal Swedish Academy for applying and extending
the use of microeconomic analysis to human behavior. This essay
is the transcript of his lecture given at the 1992 Nobel Prize
award ceremony. Becker discusses four topics: discrimination against
minorities; crime and punishment; the development and accumulation
of human capital; and the structure of families. These issues
illustrate his economic analysis of social issues. 32 pp. CONTACT:
Hoover Institution Press, Stanford University Press, Stanford,
CA 94305-6010, 415/723-3373, fax 415/723-1687, Internet  <a href="http://stanford.edu">http://hoover.stanford.edu.</a>
<P>
<B>The Whole Family Catalog: 25 Policy Planks for a Pro-Family
Future</B>
<P>
Family Research Council<HR>

<P>
The Family Research Council has published <I>The Whole Family
Catalog</I>. It contains 25 policy planks for a pro-family future.
It presents the policy goals, the action needed, and the summary
and rationale of the following issues: human life; back to basics
education; protecting the family; family friendly policies; promoting
cultural renewal; reforming federal programs that hurt families;
and other pro-family ideas. 52 pp. CONTACT: Family Research Council,
700 13th Street, N.W., Suite 500, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2100,
fax 202/393-2134, Internet <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC">http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC</a>


