<a name="taxation"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Taxation &AMP;  Budget</FONT></CENTER>
<P>

<b>How Corporate Welfare Won: Clinton and Congress Retreat from Cutting Business Subsidies,</b> by Stephen Moore and Dean Stansel<p>
<i>Policy Analysis</i> No. 254, Cato Institute<p> 
Stephen Moore, Director of Fiscal Policy Studies at the Cato Institute, and Dean Stansel, Cato Fiscal Policy analyst, demonstrate that the federal government currently spends $75 billion a year on direct subsidies to business. Despite that last year both Congress and the Clinton Adminstration pledged to attack this pervasive corporate safety net, the study finds that those promises have been largely unfulfilled. The study reveals that many corporate subsidy programs were reduced minimally, or not at all. In addition, the Clinton Administration has shown itself hostile to even the modest corporate welfare cutbacks proposed by Congress. In fact, the Administration's 1996 budget actually requested a slight increase in spending. The report concludes that an unwillingness to reduce the corporate social safety net undermines the rest of the government downsizing agenda. 29pp.  CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC  20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490, e-mail <a href="mailto: cato@cato.org">cato@cato.org</a>, Internet <a href="http://www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org.</a><p>


<b>Georgia Jobs Tax Credits: Needed Incentives or Needless Subsidies?</b> by Dr. Steve Morse<p>
<i>Issue Analysis,</i> Georgia Public Policy Foundation<p>
Dr. Steve Morris, a member of the Academic Advisory Board at the Georgia Center for Public Policy, argues that tax incentives passed in Georgia in 1994 to attract business were unnecessary and fail to address the real needs of Georgia's businesses. According to Morse, while such actions sound good in theory, in reality they have been proven to do little to affect a state's overall economic development. He bases his arguments on over thirty years of studies showing that most tax incentive programs simply give unnecessary tax incentives to businesses to do what they would have done anyway. Morse believes that if Georgia wishes to remain economically competitive in the coming years, it must abandon its current agenda of unnecessary tax incentives and adopt a policy which  focuses on factors businesses find truly important when making location decisions.  These factors include: 1) the availability of an educated and trainable workforce; 2) low taxes; 3) a high quality of life; 4) first-class research and development facilities; and 5) non-burdensome regulations. 9pp.  CONTACT: Georgia Public Policy Foundation, 2900 Chamblee-Tucker Road, Building Six, Atlanta, GA 30341-4128, 770/455-7600, fax 770/455-4355.
<p>
<b>Devolution & Block Grants,</b> by Charles L. Kennedy and Lowman S. Henry<p>
<i>Public Opinion Court,</i> Lincoln Institute of Public Opinion Research Inc.<p>
According to the Lincoln Institute, despite the growing number of programs heading back to state and local governments, much confusion and disagreement exists among government officials and private sector participants involved in the devolution process. Attempting to resolve some of the conflict and misunderstandings involved in the devolutionary process in Pennsylvania, the Lincoln Institute recently hosted a Public Opinion Court focus group.  This report documents the highlights of the focus group sessions held there, emphasizing the details of current Pennsylvania legislation dealing with the beginnings of block granting. The report also presents the thoughts of the conference's participants on the policy changes and philosophical issues involved in devolution. 7pp.  CONTACT. Carol L. Henry, Lincoln Institute of Public Opinion Research Inc., 453 Springlake Road, Harrisburg, PA 17112, 717/671-0776, fax 717/671-1176, e-mail <a href="mailto: 74157.243@compuserve.com">74157.243@compuserve.com.</a>
<p>
<b>How Title XI Ship Subsidies Sink the Taxpayer,</b> by John S. Tottie<p>
<i>Issue Analysis</i> No. 28, Citizens for a Sound Economy<p>
John S. Tottie, a Policy Analyst at Citizens for a Sound Economy, argues that the 60 year old Title XI Federal Ship Financing Guarantee Program, which guarantees loans for a wide variety of vessels and shipyard modernization projects, has accumulated $1 billion in loan defaults. Tottie posits that the case against Title XI is the case against entrenched political pork. Because the Title XI loans have a "subsidy value" and the resources available for investment are not unlimited, the government's favoritism of the shipbuilding industry also means that other goods and services that consumers want will be less plentiful. Tottie continues that any defense of Title XI must explain why the government, and not the American people, should decide how scarce economic resources are to be allocated. In conclusion, Tottie believes Title XI should be repealed. 16pp.  CONTACT: Citizens for a Sound Economy, 1250 H Street, N.W., Suite 700, Washington, DC 20005-3908, 202/783-3870, fax 202/783-4687, Internet <a href="http://www.cse.org/cse">http://www.cse.org/cse.</a>
<p>
<b>A Journalist's Handbook on Tax Reform,</b> 
by Annette Nellen<p>
Tax Foundation<p>
Annette Nellen, Associate Professor in the College of Business at San Jose State University, outlines the reasons why major federal tax reform has again surfaced and why it appears to be receiving even more attention than in prior years. In addition, Nellen overviews the proposals on the table as of December 1995. Nellen provides information on our current system, or method of government operations where appropriate, in order to foster a better understanding of a proposal. Included are a chart comparing the features of each proposal and tax calculations for a family of four and small businesses. 70pp.  CONTACT. Tax Foundation, 1250 H Street N.W., Suite 750, Washington DC 20005, 202/783-2760, fax 202/942-7675, e-mail <a href="mailto: taxfnd@intr.net">taxfnd@intr.net</a>, Internet <a href=" http://www.taxfoundation.org">http://www.taxfoundation.org.</a><p>

<b>White House Tax Theories,</b> by Alan Reynolds<p>
<i>Hudson Briefing Paper</i> No. 191, Hudson Institute<p>
Alan Reynolds, Director of Economic Research at Hudson Institute, critically anaylzes <I>The President's Council of Economic Adviser's 1996 Economic Report</i> assertion that changing tax rates have had no discernable effect on work effort, productivity, savings and economic growth. Reynolds debunks the myths presented by the CEA report which declares that the reduction of tax rates in the early 1980s was responsible for the large budget deficits that have persisted since. The Economic Report also states that whereas the impact of tax policy on savings is ambiguous, the ability of decreasing fedeal budget deficits to increase national savings is perfectly clear. Reynolds argues that the report does not bolster its finding with facts, and dismisses inconvenient truths as though they have become politically incorrect, in effect asking Americans to disregard scientific method in favor of naked politics and raw emotion. 16pp.  CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639, Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">http://www.hudson.org/hudson/</a><p>
