</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Justice, Freedom, the Flat Tax, and the Tithe
 - April 1996 Insider - Heritage</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<P>
<h3>April 1996 <i>Insider</i></h3>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Justice, Freedom, the Flat Tax, 
and the Tithe</FONT></B></CENTER>
<hr><P>
<font size=3> The last thing you should worry about when you study the matter of various flat tax 
proposals is whether it will take a 17 percent or 21 percent rate to work. From a biblical 
perspective, two far higher priorities on taxes should be the issues of justice and freedom. 
Both are recurring biblical themes, and both are terribly jeopardized by the present tax 
system in the United States. By contrast, both would be remarkably enhanced with almost 
any flat tax approach. <p>
	Complexity, almost always, is the enemy of justice. Simplicity is its friend. As soon as 
matters get complex, in virtually any venue, the opportunity for corruption takes over. When 
people can’t understand a tax code, they get either cynical or opportunistic, and neither 
attitude is congenial to evenhanded justice.<p> 
	It’s pretty hard, for example, to beat the simplicity of the tithe. No one can ever come to 
God’s court of appeals arguing that calculating 10 percent was just too difficult, or that he 
couldn’t find a tithe consultant smart enough to figure it out.<p> 
	By the same token, it’s noteworthy that God never established one tithe for the wealthy and 
another for the poor and common folk. The rate was the same, and we can assume that God 
considers that arrangement just. The book of Proverbs reminds us bluntly that we’re not to 
use two sets of standards in any financial dealings. <p>
	To be sure, almost none of the flat tax proposals now being suggested for our country is even 
yet really equal in its application. To exempt the first $36,000 (or thereabouts) of everyone’s 
income before starting to apply a 17 percent tax clearly favors the poor, who under such a 
plan would pay no tax at all. And I’m not persuaded yet that individual income from interest 
and dividends should be exempted from taxation—an idea that will appear to many to favor 
the rich, despite the argument that this income is already taxed at the corporate level. But 
that’s why I say we shouldn’t get hung up—up least yet—in the details. The simplicity of the 
proposals tends radically toward justice, and that should be appealing to biblically minded 
folks. <p>
	The other important reason for favoring a flat tax rate is that it would promote freedom. In 
one fell swoop, the flat tax minimizes the role of government in all its attempts to 
micromanage society and culture. For far too long now have we allowed great segments of 
our public life to be driven by tax considerations. The big government social engineers tinker 
constantly with the tax code: tax incentives here, tax deductions there, write-offs for this 
desirable goal, and five-year forgiveness clauses if you take on some other cause the 
government happens to like.<p> 
	The power to tax is indeed the power to destroy, but by extension it is also the power to 
shape a society’s values and ideals—and in doing so to establish which freedoms will be 
promoted and which will be restricted. So it is a wise people who place simple but strong 
restraints on their government’s ability to drill a million holes in the tax code.<p> 
	I say all this fully aware that my employer, World magazine, gets part of its lifeblood from 
tax-deductible gifts from readers—and that such revenue might be at least a little jeopardized 
if charitable contributions are no longer tax deductible. <p>
	Not to worry! For that is the very point. As long as people make gifts, even to worthy causes, 
primarily because they are tax deductible and not because that cause is passionately 
important to them, both the tax code and the government behind it are way too important. 
Yes, we may lose a few gifts to our charitable organizations—but in the end, both we and 
they will breathe so much more deeply of the great air of freedom that it will be a good trade.<p> 
	I have no idea whether a 17 percent flat tax or one at 21 percent will be needed to sustain our 
government through the transition that is coming. Either way, it’s a great bargain—not 
because of the rate, but because of where the idea ultimately takes us. <p>
 
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>Joel Belz<BR>
<BR></FONT>
<HR><P>

<B>Joel Belz </b> is the Publisher of World magazine, a 
Christian news weekly.
This Feature was adapted for his February 3, 1996<I><B>"From the Publisher"</B></I>column.
<P>
