<B><font size=3> Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Giving in the Clinton Era, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Austin Fulk and Stuart Nolan</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Capital Research Center</FONT></I>
<P>
In this comprehensive study, Austin Fulk, Research Associate, and Stuart Nolan, Visiting Fellow at Capital 
Research Center, surveyed 1993 corporate contributions from the 250 largest American corporations to 
cover 300 nonprofit public interest and special interest advocacy groups. Using available corporate and IRS 
data, Fulk and Nolan were able to identify over $36 million in contributions by 166 corporations to groups 
across the political spectrum. They found that for every $1.00 that corporations gave to conservative and 
free market policy groups, $4.07 was given to liberal groups favoring increased government spending and 
regulation. The book also uncovers a development in public affairs during the Clinton Administration: 
Although many corporations are downsizing their operations, some of them are supporting nonprofit 
advocacy groups whose lobbying activities promote big government and undermine the free enterprise 
system. The guide also lists specific grants made by Forbes 250 companies, and includes a cross-reference 
to easily check which companies fund which advocacy groups. 193 pp. CONTACT: Capital Research 
Center, 727 15th St., NW, 8th Floor, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2600, fax 202/393-2626.<p>

