Reason Foundation 1996 Policy Breakfast: Is Washington Becoming Irrelevant? 
Devolution and the Promise of Free Minds and Free Markets 
Washingon, D.C.: April 26 <p>
The Reason Foundation 1996 Policy Breakfast will be held Friday, April 26, at the 
J.W. Marriot Hotel in Washington, D.C. The breakfast will attempt to answer what the 
country will look like after devolution; what role will privatization play in the 
marginalization of Washington; and if the promise of free minds and free markets 
bridge the gap between Beltway policy makers and the American people. Participants 
will include: Rep. Chris Cox, John O’Leary, Robert Poole, and Kellyanne Fitzpatrick 
among others. CONTACT: Rich Phillips, 310/391-2245.<p>  
<hr>
The Philadelphia Society’s Thirty-Second National Meeting 
Chicago, IL: April 26-28 <p>
The Philadelphia Society’s Thirty-Second National Meeting will be held April 26-28 at the Renaissance 
Chicago Hotel (formerly the Stouffer Riviere Hotel) in Chicago. The theme of this year’s meeting is: “Is 
There Still a Legal Order?” Speakers will include Fr. Robert Sirico, Edwin Meese, III, Roger Pilon, and M. 
Stanton Evans. CONTACT: The Philadelphia Society, 109 West Main Street, North Adams, MI 49262, 
517/287-4266, fax 517/287-5814. 
 <p><hr>
Jewish Policy Center Forum Explores Jews and Public Policy: Liberalism vs. Conservatism 
Washington, D.C.: April 29, 1996 
The Jewish Policy Center will present the first in a series of forums to explore, from a Jewish perspective, 
solutions to modern social issues such as poverty, crime, and creating social justice. The first forum is 
scheduled for 7:30 p.m., April 29, 1995 at George Washington University, and is entitled “Jews: Liberal 
Roots and Conservative Solutions-Is Jewish Philosophy and Its View of Public Policy Conservative or 
Liberal in Nature?” The Speakers will include Irving Kristol, Micheal Medved, and David Novak. 
CONTACT: The Jewish Policy Center, 415 Second Street, N.E., Suite 100, Washington, D.C. 20002, 
202/547-7706, fax 202/544-2434. 
<p><hr> 
Sixth General Conference of The National Association of Scholars 
Washington, D.C.: May 3-5 
The Sixth General Conference of the National Association of Scholars will be held from May 3rd through 
5th at the Washington Marriott in Washington, D.C. The conference will provide the first public showcase 
for the new movement for higher education reform and an opportunity to discuss both its direction and 
priorities. Speakers will include: Gertrude Himmelfarb; John M. Ellis; Jery L. Martin; Jeffrey D. Wallin; 
Bruce Cole; and John J. Furedy. The conference’s principal address will be given by former Secretary of 
Education William Bennett, and the fifth Sidney Hook Memorial Award will be bestowed on Wilcomb E. 
Washburn, Director of the Office of American Studies at the Smithsonian Institution. CONTACT: National 
Association of Scholars, 575 Ewing Street, Princeton, New Jersey 08540, 609/683-7878, fax 609/683-
0316.  
