<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>NATIONAL SECURITY <BR>
&AMP; FOREIGN POLICY</FONT></CENTER>


<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/forpol/bg1066.html">
Beware of Deploying U.S. Peacekeepers on the Golan Heights,
</a></FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
by Thomas Moore and James Phillips</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 1066, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>
<P>
Thomas Moore, Deputy Director of Foreign Policy and
Defense Studies at The Heritage Foundation, and James Phillips,
Heritage Senior Policy Analyst, warn against the possibility that
the Clinton Administration might bridge the peace negotiation
gap between Israel and Syria by offering U.S. peacekeeping forces
to monitor compliance with any agreement that might come about.
Moore and Phillips offer several reasons why such a deployment
of U.S. forces should not occur, among them:
<ol><li> the Golan Heights present a more formidable peacekeeping
challenge than the existingU.S. peacekeeping mission on the Sinai Peninsula;
<li> terrorism would pose a threat to U.S. troops; 
<li> U.S.-Israel relations may be adversely affected;
<li> the cost to, and  drain on, U.S. forces.
</ol>
They call for Congress to press the Clinton Administration to rule out foreign aid
to Syria as a sweetener for a peace agreement and to maintain pressure on Syria
to halt its support of terrorism. Moore and Phillips conclude that Congress should
open debate on the Golan peacekeeping issue before it is presented with another
<I>fait accompli</I> like Haiti or Bosnia. 9 pp. CONTACT: Chris
O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue,
N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>Cuba Transition Resource Guide: <BR>
Preparing for Freedom</B>
<p>
International Republican Institute
<P>
The Cuba Transition Commitee, chaired by Jeb Bush
and composed of 44 Cuban American and U.S.-Cuba policy experts,
has produced a resource guide that provides recommended initiatives
for a three phase process for a Cuban transition to democracy
and suggests what the U.S. might do to encourage such a transition.
The guide, which also lists 66 non-governmental organizations
and 37 foundations that could play a role in the process, will
be distributed to Cuban dissidents on the island, exiles in the
U.S. and abroad, U.S. government officials, and others. 90 pp.
 CONTACT: International Republican Institute, Suite 900, 1212
New York Avenue, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20005, 202/408-9450, fax
202/408-9462, e-mail <a href="mailto: IRI@access.digex.net">IRI@access.digex.net</a><BR>

<P>
<a name="commerce"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><br>
<CENTER><font size=5>COMMERCE, INFRASTRUCTURE &AMP;
 REGULATION</CENTER></font>
<P>
<B>Unfunded Federal Mandates in Transportation: The
Case for Unilateral Devolution, <BR>
</B>by Tom McClintock
<P>
The Claremont Institute
<P>
Tom McClintock, Director, Economic and Regulatory
Affairs, at the Golden State Center for Policy Studies of the
Claremont Institute, illustrates the burden that unfunded federal
mandates have on the State of California.  McClintock suggests
that California might consider forgoing federal funds and not
be obligated to the mandates attached to them, pointing out that
while the federal assistance for programs is massive-so are the
costs of the mandates. McClintock argues that although the state
would forfeit revenues far beyond the unfunded cost of federal
mandates, there would be enormous savings from the more efficient
application of remaining revenues toward truly high-priority public
objectives. For example, McClintock concludes that if California
kicked the federal government out of state transportation policy,
it would lose $2.3 billion in federal funds. However, California
would save $1.9 billion in unnecessary mandated expenditures.
By recouping a portion of federal highway taxes, the missing $400,000
could be transferred from the federal government to the state
without an increase in the total tax burden. 12 pp. CONTACT: The
Claremont Institute, 250 West First Street, Suite 330, Claremont,
CA 91711, 909/621-6825, fax 909/626-8724, e-mail <a href="mailto: 2026935@mcimail.com:>2026935@mcimail.com</a>,
Internet <a href="/claremont">http://www.townhall.com/claremont</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>Restructuring America's Water Industry: Comparing
Investor-Owned and Government-Owned Water Systems, </B>
by Kathy Neal, <BR>
Patrick Maloney, Jonas Marson &amp; Tamer Francis
</font><P>
Reason Foundation
<P>
The performance of investor-owned water companies
is compared with government-owned water companies in California
in order to gauge the potential benefits of restructuring the
industry. The study focuses on tax subsidization, the cost of
capital, water charges, operating costs, investment income, and
capital expenditures. Among the results of an analysis of the
data are: investor-owned water companies provide comparable water
services to consumers at the same price as government-owned water
companies even though they pay taxes and do not receive extra
income; government-owned water companies receive generous tax
subsidies that otherwise could be used to lower taxes or fund
other government projects with higher priorities; the net cost
of capital is higher for government-owned water companies than
for investor-owned water companies; investor-owned companies are
substantially more efficient in their operation than government-owned
water companies; and government-owned water companies receive
a substantial amount of non-operating income from excess cash
balances and investments. The authors conclude that the decision
to have government entities provide water to consumers should
be reconsidered, since investor-owned companies can provide this
same function at the same cost without subsidies or tax-exemptions.
23 pp.  CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite
400, Los Angeles, CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.<BR>

<P>
<B>Washington State Regulatory Reform: Accomplishments
and Comparisons, <BR>
</B>by Elaine Ramel
Davis
<P>
Washington Institute
<P>
Washington Institute Senior Research Fellow Elaine
Ramel Davis updates the status of regulatory reform in Washington
State. Davis summarizes the accomplishments of the Regulatory
Reform Act and compares them with the Institute's earlier recommendations.
Davis believes that the RRA was a good start to the process of
reducing the amount of government regulation in Washington state.
However she also illustrates that while the RRA &quot;slows the
flow&quot; of new and increasingly onerous state regulations,
more needs to be done to end overburdensome regulations. 5 pp.
CONTACT: Washington Institute for Policy Studies, 999 Third Ave.,
Suite 1060, Seattle, WA  98104, 206/467-9561, fax 206/938-6313.
<BR>

<P>
<B>FDA Hazards: How FDA Red Tape Impacts Entrepreneurs
and the U.S. Economy, <BR>
</B>by Raymond Keating
<P>
Small Business Survival Foundation

<P>
Raymond Keating, Chief Economist with the Small Business
Survival Foundation, reviews the responsibilities, tactics and
strategies, and budget of the FDA, as well as the administration's
impact on entrepreneurs. Keating recommends the following reforms:
<ol><li>scrapping the FDA in favor of a smaller agency geared toward
safety and education;<br><li>subjecting manufacturers and approval
enterprises  to the incentives of a sound legal system;<br><li>allowing
manufacturers to distribute information regarding off-label uses
of drugs, such as independent studies and journal articles;<br><li>
annual congressional scrutiny of the federal agency's enforcement
powers, as well as its processes and standards for determining
what products fall under its jurisdiction;<br><li>negotiating and
entering into agreements with other nations to recognize each
other's drug and medical device approvals;<br><li>enhancing incentives
for investment in dynamic industries, like pharmaceuticals and
medical devices. 25 pp.</ol><br>
CONTACT: Small Business Survival Foundation,
1320 18th Street, N.W., Suite 200, Washington, DC 20036, 202/785-0238,
fax 202/822-8118, e-mail <a href="mailto: rstikes@sbsc.org">rstikes@sbsc.org</a>, Internet <a href="/sbsc">http://www.sbsc.org</a>.
<BR>

<P>
<B>Hazardous to our Health? FDA Regulation of Health
Care Products, </B>edited
by Robert Higgs
<P>
The Independent Institute


<P>
Robert Higgs, Research Director, The Independent
Institute, Ronald Hansen, Associate Dean for Academic Affairs
at the William E. Simon Graduate School of Business Administration,
and  Paul Rubin, Professor of Economics at Emory University, examine
FDA's regulation of health care products. The book's introduction
and afterword place the activities of FDA into a larger perspective
by illustrating how the agency acquired its vast powers, how it
uses those powers, and what harm caused by FDA could be diminished
by abolishing the agency. Other chapters argue that FDA, largely
regarded as a scientific body devoted to protecting public health,
is in fact a highly politicized body, often harming the public
health. Another chapter focuses on the restrictions that FDA places
on the marketing of drugs. According to the authors, these advertising
restrictions assume that consumers should be treated as if they
are unsophisticated and easily misled, and that doctors are not
reliable judges of medicines. The authors conclude that the root
cause of the harm caused by FDA regulations arise from the enormous
discretion Congress has given the agency. 113 pp.  CONTACT: The
Independent Institute, 134 98th Ave., Oakland, CA 94603, 510/632-1366,
fax 510/568-6040.<BR>

<P>
<B>The Truth About Income Inequality,</B>
<BR>
by John Hinderaker and Scott Johnson
<P>
Center for the American Experiment
<P>
John Hinderaker and Scott Johnson, attorneys in Minneapolis,
examine liberal claims that there is a widening income inequality
and a disappearing middle class in America. They illustrate that
these claims have been based, almost universally, on biased analyses
which manipulate and distort the underlying economic facts. Overall,
they conclude that basic economic data does not support the gloomy
picture promoted by liberals. Furthermore, Hinderaker and Johnson
write that the data shows that the last 25 years does not represent
an upward or downward trend for middle-and lower-income Americans.
The data also does not suggest that higher taxes, increased government
spending, or hyper-regulation of the economy will benefit middle-income
or lower-income citizens. 18 pp. CONTACT: Center for the American
Experiment, 12 S. 6th St., Minneapolis, MN 55402, 612/338-3605.
<BR>

<P>
<B>The Value of Fringe Benefits and Tenure in Wisconsin:
Public Versus Private, <BR>
</B>by Richard Cebula
<P>
Wisconsin Policy Research Institute
<P>
In this study, Richard Cebula, an economist at Georgia
Tech, examines the differentials in the levels of fringe benefits
provided to full-time workers between the public and private sectors
in Wisconsin. He also examines the value of tenure or its equivalent
in the Wisconsin public school system at the primary and secondary
levels. Cebula examines each major category of fringe benefits
and then all benefits combined, concluding that the overall fringe-benefit
value appears to be 36% higher in the public sector than in the
private sector. 16 pp. CONTACT: Wisconsin Policy Research Institute,
3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukee, WI  53211, 414/963-0600, fax
414/963-4230.<BR>

<P>
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect552.html"><B>A Tale of Two Pesos: A Comparison of Currency Policies in Mexico and Argentina, </B></a> by
Steve Hanke
<P>
<I>Heritage Lecture</I>
No. 552, The Heritage Foundation


<P>
Steve Hanke, Professor of Applied Economics at Johns
Hopkins University and an advisor to Argentina's Minister of Economy,
compares the currency policies of Mexico and Argentina. Argentina,
according to Hanke, appears to have committed itself to maintaining
a stable currency. Mexico's monetary policy, on the other hand,
is in disarray. Hanke points out that Mexicans have called for
a sound peso, but that politicians from the three major parties
and their technocrat advisors have not been able to agree on an
exchange rate policy. So far Argentina's currency reforms seem
to be working. Hanke lays out several specific areas where Mexico
can learn and benefit from Argentina's experience. 11 pp.  CONTACT:
Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail <a href="mailto: Insider@heritage.org">Insider@heritage.org</a>.<BR>

<P>
<B>Speaking Freely: The Public Interest in Unfettered
Speech</B>
<P>
The Media Institute

<P>
This publication suggests that Congress and a willing
FCC have proven surprisingly eager to regulate what is seen and
heard on television and radio. Included are several essays by
the following authors: John Corry, columnist for the <I>American
Spectator</I>, on TV Violence; Doug Bandow, Senior Fellow at the
Cato Institute, on indecency; Adam Thierer, Fellow at the Heritage
Foundation, on children's television; Daniel Troy, partner, Wiley
Rein &amp; Fielding, on commercial speech; and E. Brant Gustavson,
President, National Religious Broadcasters, on the Fairness Doctrine.
113 pp.  CONTACT: The Media Institute, Suite 301, 1000 Potomac
Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20007, 202/298-7512, fax 202/337-7092,
e-mail <a href="mailto: tmi@clark.net">tmi@clark.net</a><BR>
