<a href="#nhp">New Heritage Papers</a>
<P>
<a name="national"></a>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>NATIONAL SECURITY <BR>
&AMP; FOREIGN POLICY</FONT></CENTER>


<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/forpol/bg1067.html">Getting Nato Back to Basics,</a></FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
by John Hillen</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 1067, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Heritage Policy Analyst John Hillen writes that NATO's
involvement in the peace operation in Bosnia is a clear signal
that the Atlantic Alliance has strayed far from its original mission
of preventing the domination of Europe by a hostile power. Hillen
argues that NATO should not reinvent itself to serve as a pan-European
alliance of collective security, and calls for a NATO Revitalization
Act to refocus the alliance and preserve American support for
the U.S. role in Europe. 14 pp.  CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The
Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington,
D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail Insider@heritage.org.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/forpol/bgup267.html">Clinton's Bosnia Venture Threatens What it Is Supposed to Uphold - The Atlantic Alliance,</a> <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Thomas Moore
&amp; John Hillen </FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Backgrounder Update</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 267, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Thomas Moore, Heritage Deputy Director of Foreign
Policy and Defense Studies, and John Hillen, Heritage Policy Analyst,
warn that NATO's involvement in the Bosnia peace process threatens
the credibility of the Atlantic Alliance by subordinating it to
the United Nations command structure. Moore and Hillen conclude
that Congress should: 1) lay down additional markers by which
success or failure can be measured; 2) establish basic guidelines
for implementing the agreement; and 3) express strong support
for NATO and NATO expansion. 7 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain,
The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington,
D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail Insider@heritage.org.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>China's Economic Revolution and its Implications
for Sino-U.S. Relations, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Ramon Myers</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Essays in Public Policy</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
The Hoover Institution</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Ramon Myers, Hoover Senior Fellow, addresses the
main issues that will influence the future of relations between
the U.S. and China in the coming decades, including  economic
friction, international security interests, and human rights.
Meyers calls for the following steps to be taken to forge a close
working relationship with China: 1) establishment of annual summit
meetings and a hot-line communication system between Sino-U.S.
leaders; 2) creation of a high-level Sino-U.S. committee of officials
and experts to manage potential economic friction; 3) expansion
of scholarly exchange programs; and 4) encouragement of local
government exchanges. 15 pp.  CONTACT: Hoover Institution Press,
Stanford University Press, Stanford, CA  94305-6010, 415/723-3373,
fax 415/725-8990, Internet <a href="http://hoover.stanford.edu">http://hoover.stanford.edu</a>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Taiwan and East Asian Security, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Robert Dujarric</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Hudson Briefing Paper</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 186, The Hudson Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Hudson Institute Research Fellow Robert Dujarric
calls for Asia and the U.S. to work to steer China toward cooperation
and collaboration on the issue of Taiwan, not confrontation, as
the recent tensions between Taiwan and China threaten the prosperity
of both Asia and the U.S. A key element to achieving this cooperation,
according to Dujarric, would be the establishment of multilateral
security institutions which</FONT><I><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">would provide a
forum for military and civilian cooperation among Asian nations,
ensuring continued peace and prosperity in the region. 12 pp.
CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center, P.O. Box 26-919,
Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, fax 317/545-9639, <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">http://www.hudson.org/hudson</a>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Foreign Policy in the '96 Race</FONT></B>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Orbis</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
Winter 1996, Foreign Policy Research Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>This issue features a series of articles on the subject
of foreign policy in the '96 presidential race. The first, <I>The
U.S. Electoral Cycle since 1944</I> by David Eisenhower, argues
that U.S. foreign policy will not be a major issue in the 1996
presidential race. In <I>The Populist Revival and Foreign Affairs</I>
by A.J. Bacevich, it is argued that the political realignment
established in the 1994 elections, though not caused by foreign
policy issues, will have substantial implications for future American
diplomacy. Bacevich believes that a populist tide will oppose
a global agenda. In <I>Even Foreign Policy Is a Local Affair</I>,
author Patrick Lloyd Hatcher believes that foreign policy issues,
will indeed, play a large role in the 1996 campaign, as the free
trade/isolationism and downsizing/defense contracts issues will
be of interest to local constituencies. 52 pp.  CONTACT: Foreign
Policy Research Institute, 3615 Chestnut St., Philadelphia, PA
19104, 215/382-0685, fax 215/382-0131.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Crisis and Growth in Israel: </FONT></B>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Squaring the Circle, </FONT></B><font size=3>by
Alvin Rabushka</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>IASPS Quarterly Report</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
Vol. 4, No. 4, The Institute for Advanced Strategic and Political
Studies</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Alvin Rabushka, Senior Fellow at the Hoover Institution
and Director of the Division for Economic Policy Research at IASPS,
calls for Israel to give up U.S. aid so that it may establish
its economic independence. He argues that Israel's apparent economic
success is only a facade. The real story, according to Rabushka,
is that &quot;Israel is besieged by one economic crisis after
another: power failures, bankrupt kibbutzim, a perpetual housing
crisis, confiscatory taxation, trade restrictions, a massive trade
deficit in both goods and services, budget deficits, high interest
rates, one failed attempt after another at privatization, and
so on.&quot; Despite these chronic problems,  Rabushka notes that
Israel has been able to sustain unparalleled growth for one simple
reason, Israelis live off the money of others-totaling $9 billion
and equaling one-eighth of all goods and services that Israelis
consume. 8 pp. CONTACT: Institute for Advanced Strategic and Political
Studies, 10 Hatayassim St., Jerusalem 92509, Israel, 972-2-638171,
fax 972-2-638176.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>A Mexican Tragedy,</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
by Allan H. Meltzer</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>On the Issues</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
No. 5825, American Enterprise Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Allan Meltzer, Visiting Scholar at AEI, comments
on recent financial troubles in Mexico and reviews the chain of
events that have lead to Mexico's unstable economy. Despite positive
economic forecasts in 1994 with the approval of NAFTA, the year
ended with a damaged political structure, major devaluation of
the peso and an overall policy failure. According to Meltzer,
the major players in the tragic events in Mexico were high officials
in the Mexican and U.S. governments and the International Monetary
Fund. Meltzer outlines what Mexico should have done as well as
lessons to be learned from the events of 1994-1995. He concludes
that the role of governments and international agencies in international
finance should be reduced. &quot;Governments that know they must
bear the consequences of their mistaken policies will be more
inclined to moderate those policies.&quot;  6 pp.  CONTACT: American
Enterprise Institute, 1150 17th St., NW, Washington, DC  20036,
202/862-5800, fax 202/862-7178.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<a name="commerce"></a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>COMMERCE, INFRASTRUCTURE &AMP; REGULATION</FONT></CENTER>


<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/regulation/fyi84.html">How the Telecom Bill Gives Away $70 Billion in Family Tax Relief to the Broadcast Industry</a>, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Adam Thierer
&amp; John Barry</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>F.Y.I. </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
84, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>A clause buried deep in the 300-page Telecom Bill
requires the FCC to carry out an ill-concieved plan to <I>give
</I>America's broadcast industry additional licenses to use part
of the electromagnetic spectrum to broadcast digital televison
services. Experts at the FCC have estimated that <I>auctioning</I>
off the spectrum could raise as much as $70 billion. According
to Thierer &amp; Barry, $70 billion could pay for the following:
1) three years of the congressionally approved $500-per-child
tax credit that benefits 28 million families raising 51 million
children; 2) the entire economic growth tax package proposed by
Congress, including the capital gains tax cut; or 3) $70 billion
in debt reduction that would save taxpayers nearly $3 billion
each year in interest payments on the national debt. Thierer &amp;
Barry advocate auctioning the spectrum. 4 pp. CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain,
The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington,
D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961, e-mail Insider@heritage.org.</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Telecommunications Reform Bills: CFA Claims Just
Don't Ring True, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Wayne Leighton</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Issue Analysis </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
15, Citizens for a Sound <BR>
Economy Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>The Consumer Federation of America issued a report
in October that claimed that the telecommunications bills in Congress
would cost American consumers billions of dollars. According to
Wayne Leighton, Regulatory Economist at Citizens for a Sound Economy,
this analysis is faulty and based on a misunderstanding of the
legislation and the effects of regulatory reform in telecommunications.
Leighton argues that deregulation and competition would save consumers
money, while overall efficiency gains could total $30 billion.
11 pp. CONTACT: Citizens for a Sound Economy, 1250 H St., NW,
Suite 700, Washington, DC  20005-3908, 202/783-3870, fax 202/783-4687.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Competitive Telecommunications: <BR>
Four Principles for Free Market Reform</FONT></B>
<P>
<I><font size=3>The State Factor </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">Vol.
21, No. 7, American Legislative Exchange Council</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>The American Legislative Exchange Council proposes
four principles for free market reform in telecommunications 
that should be adapted by each state to fit its own unique statutes,
circumstances and time frames: 1) competition, not regulation,
should shape the telecommunications industry; 2) where regulation
is necessary, it should be competitively neutral and equally applied
to all providers; 3) universal service should be preserved; and
4) all providers should be permitted to compete in all markets.
ALEC belivieves that these four principles are a way to ensure
that consumers get the greatest benefit from telecommunications
innovations by encouraging competition and opening markets. 8
pp. CONTACT: American Legislative Exchange Council, 910 17th St.,
NW, 5th Floor, Washington, DC  20006, 202/466-3800, fax 202/466-3801.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>The Green Bay Packers, America's Only Not-for-Profit,
Major League Sports Franchise, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Daniel Alesch
</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>Wisconsin Policy Research Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>University of Wisconsin-Green Bay Professor Daniel
Alesch illustrates the unique situation of the National Football
League's Green Bay Packers. The Packers are the league's only
publicly owned, not-for-profit franchise. Despite Green Bay's
relatively small population of 97,000 people, the team has succeeded
in Green Bay for 77 years. Alesch shows the economic benefits
of the Packers to the local communities, while explaining how
the Packer franchise model might be able to offer a new approach
to strategic community analysis. 31 pp. CONTACT: Wisconsin Policy
Research Institute, 3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukie, WI 53211,
414/963-0600, fax 414/963-4230.</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3><a href="/heritage/library/categories/trade/lect546.html">Advancing American Business Interests Through APEC</a>, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Hon. Barbara
Franklin, Stuart Allan, Philip Vaughn, and Dan Amstutz</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Heritage Lecture </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
546, The Heritage Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>This discussion dealt with the subject of using the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum (APEC) to advance American
business interests. Panelists included: Hon. Barbara Franklin,
former U.S. Commerce Secretary and Chairman, American Trader Initiative
Advisory Council; Stuart Allan, Director, Office of Economic Policy,
Bureau of East Asian and Pacific Affairs U.S. Department of State;
Philip Vaughn, Director, Government Relations, Flour Corporation;
and Dan Amstutz, President, North American Export Grain Association.
Topics included a discussion of how to overcome the obstacles
to reaching a free trade zone with Asia by the year 2020. 12 pp.
 CONTACT: Chris O'Scannlain, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002, 202/546-4400, fax 202/544-0961,
e-mail Insider@heritage.org.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Labor Unions &amp; &quot;Consumers United with
Employees&quot;: The Campaign Against Food Lion,</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
by Thomas DiLorenzo</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>The Capital Research Center</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>This study looks at the strategy employed by labor
unions known as a &quot;corporate campaign.&quot; Capital Research
Center Senior Fellow Thomas DiLorenzo illustrates how a &quot;corporate
campaign&quot; organized by a group calling itself Consumers United
with Employees (CUE) was really a public relations ploy against
Food Lion backed by the United Food and Commercial Workers (UFCW).
 A tactic used by CUE to smear the reputation of Food Lion was
to use headline grabbing press releases that claimed that a &quot;study&quot;
of Food Lion had &quot;discovered&quot; instances of health violations
within the chain. The reports attempted to mislead the media by
only citing Food Lion errors-some legitimate, some questionable-while
omitting the fact that other grocery chains have similar lapses
in procedures. DiLorenzo writes that the tactics used by the UFCW
do not help the consumer as they claim, instead, they cause the
price of groceries to climb by running the low-price, non-union
chains out of business. 8 pp.  CONTACT: Capital Research Center,
727 15th St., NW, 8th Floor, Washington, DC  20005, 202/393-2600,
fax 202/393-2626.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Cracked Foundation: Repealing the Davis-Bacon
Act, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Richard
Vedder and Lowell Gallaway</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Policy Study </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
127, Center for the Study <BR>
of American Business</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Richard Vedder, John M. Olin Visiting Professor of
Labor Economics at CSAB, and Lowell Gallaway, Distinguished Professor
of Economics at Ohio University, illustrate the racial implications
of the Davis-Bacon Act (which requires contractors of federally
funded projects to pay union scale, or &quot;prevailing&quot;
wages). Vedder and Galloway write that the bill was originally
crafted to protect northern white labor against cheaper black
labor from other regions. In addition, they suggest that the legislation
was not race-neutral in its impact, and very likely has caused
a lack of minority participation in the construction industry.
Vedder and Gallaway give a full historical background on the enactment
of the legislation, including the fact that in the two decades
before the passage of Davis-Bacon there was a significant  growth
in the number of black employees outside the South in major construction
crafts. The study concludes that Davis-Bacon, like other minimum
wage laws, has increased unemployment for all groups; but its
negative impact has affected black construction workers disproportionately.
28 pp.  CONTACT: Center for the Study of American Business, Washington
University, Campus Box 1208, St. Louis, MO 63130-4899, 314/935-5630,
fax 314/935-5688.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Free Markets, Free Choices: Women in the Workforce,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Katherine Post
&amp; Michael Lynch</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Briefing</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">This paper, by Pacific Research
Institute Public Policy Fellows Katherine Post and Michael Lynch,
examines the role of women in the marketplace today. The study
looks at the glass ceiling  and gender wage gap myths and exposes
the underlying factors primarily responsible for every women's
individual achievements, namely, her personal choices. 22 pp.
 CONTACT: Pacific Research Institute, 755 Sansome St., San Francisco,
CA  94111, 415/989-0833, fax 415/989-2411, e-mail PRIPP@aol.com
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Stress Claims in Michigan: Workers Compensation
Entitlement for Mental Disability, </FONT></B><font size=3>by
J&uuml;rgen Skoppek</FONT>
<P>
<font size=3>Mackinac Center for Public Policy</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>In the state of Michigan, the worker's compensation
system was developed as a way for workers who suffer on-the-job
physical injuries to be quickly and fairly compensated for medical
costs and lost income. In recent years, however, an ambiguous
new area of law has developed under workman's compensation that
allows workers to claim injuries due to alleged on-the-job mental
stress. This has lead to complications in Michigan as how to judge
properly whether a claimant is worthy of compensation. This report
illustrates how the worker's compensation system works, its problems
with claims for mental stress injuries, the history of case and
statutory law regarding mental stress, and where the issue stands
today after a crucial 1994 Michigan Supreme Court decision. 36
pp. CONTACT: Mackinac Center for Public Policy, 119 Ashman St.,
P.O. Box 568, Midland, MI  48640, 517/631-0900, fax 517/631-0964.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>Privatizing Emergency Medical Service: How Cities
Can Cut Costs and Save Lives, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Robert Poole</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>How-To Guide </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
14, Reason Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Robert Poole, President of the Reason Foundation,
argues that cities could save millions of dollars and improve
response times to 911 emergency calls by privatizing Emergency
Medical Service. In Los Angeles alone, the cost to the taxpayer
for these services is $45.6 million a year. Reason estimates that
contracting with a private provider for certain EMS/paramedic
services would reduce the cost to taxpayers by two-thirds. Poole
concludes that cities and counties should reorganize their EMS
systems by creating a public-private partnership in which the
fire department provides first response service and private ambulance
firms provide all paramedic treatment and transport for all 911
medical calls. The results, according to Poole, would be reduction
of cost to the taxpayer, greater accountability, and quicker response
times. 18 pp. CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd.,
Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>A Federal Privatization Agenda, </FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Robert Poole</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Testimony </FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">No.
4, Reason Foundation</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>This report is the transcript of testimony given
to the Senate Budget Committee by Reason Foundation President
Robert Poole. In his testimony, Poole advocates two forms of privatization
for the federal government, asset divestiture and infrastructure
partnerships. Poole illustrates how such federal enterprises as
the U.S. Postal Service and the Corporation for Public Broadcasting
can be privatized, and lists federal assets, such as commodity
lands, defense reserves, the strategic petroleum reserve, and
government buildings and land that could be utilized better under
private ownership. Poole also discusses the subject of infrastructure
partnership and how the federal government can promote private
ownership and operation of infrastructure. He concludes his testimony
with five general principles for privatization and summarizes
the issues associated with implementing a privatization agenda.
16 pp.  CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite
400, Los Angeles, CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><font size=3>What went Wrong With Work? The Industrial Counterrevolution,
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Brink Lindsey</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Reason</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">,
February 1996 </FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>Progressive intellectuals, according to trade attorney
Brink Lindsey, corrupted capitalism by convincing Americans that
bigger is best for labor, business, and government. However, Lindsay
argues that the triumvirate of Big Government, Big Business, and
Big Labor is collapsing. Big Labor has seen this change first,
as unionization of the private sector labor force decline from
36 percent in 1953 to only 11 percent today. Meanwhile, large
American corporations, argued to be immune from market forces
by intellectuals in the 1960s, have been &quot;restructured&quot;
or &quot;reengineered&quot; in the form of middle-management layoffs.
Now, writes Lindsey, it is Big Government's turn. 10 pp. CONTACT:
Reason Foundation, 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite 400, Los Angeles,
CA  90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395.<BR>
