<B><font size=3>The Wisconsin Welfare Revolution, <BR>
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by Lawrence Mead</FONT>
<P>
<I><font size=3>Wisconsin Interest</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
Vol. 4, No. 2, Wisconsin Policy Research Institute</FONT>


<P>
<font size=3>In this article, New York University Professor Lawrence
Mead examines why Wisconsin's welfare caseload declined 26% since
reforms and new programs were enacted in 1987. According to state
figures, welfare in the average Wisconsin county fell 42%, while
some small counties recorded decreases of as much as 66%. Mead
found that the decline in welfare recipients was due less to Wisconsin's
now thriving economy and more to the priority that reforms placed
on self reliance. Furthermore, Mead writes that Governor Thompson's
conservative, but not necessarily anti-government, policy was
successful in changing the attitudes of most welfare personnel.
Indeed, most welfare officials, according to Mead, appreciated
that the Governor challenged them with the responsibility of getting
recipients to work, rather than just handing out aid. 8 pp.  CONTACT:
Wisconsin Policy Research Institute, 3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukee,
WI  53211, 414/963-0600, fax 414/963-4230.<BR>
